# TCL(Transaction Control Language)
- a subset of SQL commands used to manage transactions in a relational database.
- it ensures data integrity by allowing user to save,undo, or mark points within a tansaction.
- Used to maintain consistency, crash/erroe recovery, partial undo and control isolation

Functions 
1. COMMIT;
- saves all changes permanentlu
2. ROLLBACK;
- undoes changes since the last COMMIT.
3. SAVEPOINT;
- creates a marker to roll back to.
4. ROLLBACK TO SAVEPOINT;
- rolls back only to the defined savepoint
5. SET TRANSACTION
- defines transaction properties(like isolation level)
- SET TRANSACTION ISOLATION LEVEL SERIALIZABLE;

Example

BEGIN;
INSERT INTO eventSchedule(event_name,event_date,start_time,end_time,created_at,city)
VALUES('Test event','2026-01-10','2023-11-25','12:00:00','09:00:00','Kathmandu');
SAVEPOINT sp1;
UPDATE eventSchedule SET city='Pokhara' WHERE event_name='Test event';
ROLLBACK TO sp1; -- undo the update, but kepp the insert
COMMIT; -- permanently save the insert

